finalparticle
  <span class\="show">ma</span><span class\="hide">question tone<br>at the end of a sentence, turns it into a yes/no question<br>on its own, means something like "huh?", or indicates general confusion<br>can also be used to create rhetorical questions, usually by not using a question intonation</span> // question: "Huh?" "Is that right?", or general confusion
  <span class\="show">-tto</span><span class\="hide">suggestion tone; "Let's..." or "How about you..."<br>when used with a question intonation, it comes off as a gentle proposal<br>when used as a statement, has a more confident or direct feel, like the English imperative "Let's..."<br>a negative feeling can be created by putting <i>yong</i> as its own word after, or contracting <i>-tto</i> to <i>-ttoyo</i></span> // suggestion: "Let's..." "How about you..."
  <span class\="show">matto</span><span class\="hide">suggestive tone; "What if..."<br>when asked as a question, it comes off as less direct, more indecisive and worrying<br>when used as a statement, it suggests the speaker already has a firm opinion on what's being said</span> // what if
  <span class\="show">-chi</span><span class\="hide">derived from <i>chisa</i>, the full phrase for "yes". has a few common uses:<br>to emphasise a sentence, bring attention to ir, or in some cases, add urgency<br>to assert ones confidence in a statement<br>to introduce new or contrasting information, or to rectify incorrect information</span>
  <span class\="show">-ndokana</span><span class\="hide">indirect tone suffix: "Just so you know..."<br>it presents the statement as largely informative, removing any implied request or obligation to act on the information. <i>yaso</i> can also be added to make it even gentler<br>cannot be used with questions or imperatives</span>
  <span class\="show">-dakanei</span><span class\="hide">annoyance tone suffix: "Seriously?!" or "Are you for real?"<br>originally derived from <i>dakanei to hamyonggo</i> "if (someone) does it, then I won't be needed", used to point out chores or work left undone while expressing frustration about it. has been shortened greatly, and is now solely used to express frustration<br>can be attached to other sentence-final particles</span>
  <span class\="show">gaenma</span><span class\="hide">technically not a final particle, but is used in about the same place. has a meaning of "I hope" or "there is a hope".<br>when used with the plain form of a verb, it more commonly takes on a meaning of "may", such as "may your skies be clear", expressing both a hope that something will happen and urging it to be true.</span>
  <span class\="show">yaso</span><span class\="hide">technically not a final particle, but is used in about the same place. meaning "please", it's most often used with plain form verbs to turn them into a request or obligation, but can also be used on its own.</span>
  <span class\="show">pei</span><span class\="hide">used after a sentence to mean "it seems". can take a variety of verb tenses, separate from the main sentence</span>

